# WASMnism: WASM-Powered Content Moderation — Edge Benchmark

You are building a portable WASM-powered content moderation gateway deployed as WebAssembly across WASM-first edge platforms, producing a decision-grade price-per-performance scorecard for a blog post.

## Two-Branch Strategy

- **`rules-only` branch (Tier 1)**: WASM-first performance/price comparison — Akamai Functions vs Fastly Compute vs Cloudflare Workers. Rules-only pipeline, no ML.
- **`ml-inference` branch (Tier 2)**: ML inference at the edge — Akamai Functions vs AWS Lambda. Embedded MiniLMv2 toxicity classifier.

## Architecture

- Rust workspace at `edge-gateway/` with shared `core/` logic and per-platform adapters.
- Core pipeline (rules-only): normalize → hash → leetspeak expand → prohibited scan → PII → injection → verdict.
- Svelte dashboard at `frontend/` — built to static files, served by Spin's fileserver component.
- Akamai Functions is the primary deployment. Live at: https://0ae93a16-62c9-44cc-8a2b-23f7c6b9bae1.fwf.app/

## Hard Requirements

- Gateway must return identical JSON schema across all platforms for the same inputs.
- Benchmark runs must be repeatable (N runs, report median).
- Security is job zero: never commit API keys, secrets, passwords, IP addresses, or credentials.
- Use .example templates for any config containing environment-specific values.

## Context Rules

- Never ask the user to paste tokens, kubeconfigs, API keys, or credentials into chat.
- PROJECT_STATE and OPERATIONS files are private — never commit them.

## Agent Procedures

- Read `AGENT_HANDOVER.md` first. It provides narrative context, timeline, lessons learned, and reading order for all other docs.
- Read `PROJECT_STATE.md` for current deploy/benchmark status, known issues, and pending tasks.
- Read `docs/AGENT_PLAYBOOK.md` for operational procedures, naming conventions, and checklists.
- Update `PROJECT_STATE.md` at the end of every session with what changed.
- Update `AGENT_HANDOVER.md` if you make significant decisions, discover bugs, or change strategic direction.
- Use `make report` for all scorecard generation — never run pandoc/weasyprint directly.
- Use `make security-check` before staging commits.
- Run `bench/validate-results.py` before building any scorecard to catch stale data.
- Never re-run benchmarks without first checking if fresh data already exists in `results/`.

## Security Rules

- Never hardcode: API keys, secret keys, passwords, IP addresses, account IDs, or inference service URLs.
- Use environment variables or secret managers for all sensitive config.
- Provide .env.example and cost-config.example.yaml with placeholders only.
- Do not log secrets, credentials, or PII.
- Benchmark result JSON may contain IPs — keep raw results out of git (use .gitignore).
- Run `make security-check` before any commit to scan for secrets, IPs, PII, and API tokens.
- The pre-push hook (`scripts/pre-push-check.sh`) blocks pushes containing sensitive data. Never bypass it with `--no-verify`.

## Target Platforms

- Tier 1 — WASM-first (rules-only branch): Akamai Functions (Spin), Fastly Compute, Cloudflare Workers
- Tier 2 — ML inference (ml-inference branch): Akamai Functions (Spin) vs AWS Lambda

## Platform Tiers (Pricing)

- All platforms must use paid tiers (or best-effort equivalent) for fair benchmarking.
- Cloudflare Workers: Workers Paid plan ($5/mo)
- Fastly Compute: Usage-based (no free/paid distinction)
- Akamai Functions: Preview/beta (document current status)
- AWS Lambda: Standard pricing (Tier 2 / ml-inference branch only)

## Project Structure

- `edge-gateway/` — Rust workspace (core + adapters + tools + models)
- `frontend/` — Svelte dashboard (build output → `edge-gateway/adapters/spin/static/`)
- `bench/` — k6 benchmark scripts
- `deploy/` — Deployment scripts
- `cost/` — Cost model
- `docs/` — Benchmark contract, moderation guide

## Blog Post Alignment

This project will produce a blog post. Structure: executive summary, narrative hook, disclosure, architecture, measurement contract, benchmark results, reproduce instructions. Use median of 7 runs; client-side timing as source of truth.
